===Etymology===
1580, from {{bor|en|frm|massacre}}, from {{der|en|fro|macacre|macacre, marcacre, macecre, macecle|slaughterhouse, butchery}}, usually thought to be deverbal from {{der|en|fro|macecrer}}, {{m|fro|macecler||to slaughter}}, though the noun seems to be attested somewhat earlier. It is also found in {{der|en|ML.|mazacrium||massacre, slaughter, killing”, also “the head of a newly killed stag}}. Further origin disputed:
* From {{der|en|la|macellum||butcher shop}}.
* From {{der|en|VL.|-}} *''matteuculāre'', from *''matteuca'' (cf. {{m|fr|massue}}), from {{der|en|LL.|-}} ''mattea'', ''mattia'', from Latin {{m|la|mateola}}.
* From {{der|en|gml|*matskelen||to massacre}} (compare {{cog|de|metzeln||massacre}}), frequentative of {{m|gml|matsken|matsken, matzgen|to cut, hew}}, from {{der|en|gmw-pro|*maitan}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*maitaną||to cut}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*mei-||small}}. Akin to {{cog|goh|meizan||to cut}} among others.
* Note also {{cog|ar|مَجْزَرَة}}, originally “spot where animals are slaughtered”, now also “massacre”, and in Maghrebi Arabic “slaughterhouse”. Derived from {{m|ar|جَزَرَ||to cut, slaughter}}.

